    "question": "Imagine you're planning a space mission to Mercury and need to calculate how long your spacecraft will take to complete one orbit around the Sun, given Mercury's average distance from the Sun is 58 million kilometers. The mass of the Sun is 1.99x10^30 kg. How many Earth days will your spacecraft take to orbit the Sun once, closely following Mercury's path?\n\nRetrieved documents:\n[Document 1]\n\\section{Mass of Sun from Gravitational Constant}\nTags: Celestial Mechanics\n\n\\begin{theorem}\nLet the gravitational constant be known.\nLet the mean distance from the Earth to the sun be known.\nThen it is possible to calculate the mass of the sun.\n\\end{theorem}\n\n\\begin{proof}\nFrom Kepler's Third Law of Planetary Motion:\n:$T^2 = \\left({\\dfrac {4 \\pi^2} {G M} }\\right) a^3$\nwhere:\n:$T$ is the orbital period of the planet in question (in this case, the Earth)\n:$a$ is the distance from the planet (in this case, the Earth) to the sun\n:$M$ is the mass of the sun\n:$G$ is the gravitational constant\nIn MKS units:\n:$T = 60 \\times 60 \\times 24 \\times 365.24219 \\, \\mathrm s$ by definition of year\n:$a = 149 \\, 597 \\, 870 \\, 700 \\, \\mathrm m$ by definition of astronomical unit\n:$G = 6.674 \\times 10^{-11} \\, \\mathrm N \\, \\mathrm m^2 \\, \\mathrm{kg}^{-2}$ by measurement, as by hypothesis.\n:$M$ will be the result in kilograms.\nThus:\n{{begin-eqn}}\n{{eqn | l = M\n      | r = \\dfrac {4 \\pi^2 a^3} {T^2 G}\n      | c = \n}}\n{{eqn | r = \\frac {4 \\times \\left({3.14159}\\right)^2 \\times \\left({149.60 \\times 10^9}\\right)^3} {\\left({31.557 \\times 10^6}\\right) \\times 6.674 \\times 10^{-11} }\n      | c = \n}}\n{{end-eqn}}\nThe calculation has been left as an exercise for anyone who has the patience.\n{{qed}}\n\\end{proof}\n\n\n\n[Document 2]\n\\begin{definition}[Definition:Neptune]\n'''Neptune''' is the eighth planet of the solar system from the sun.\nIts orbit lies mainly between those of Uranus and Pluto, although the latter comes closer to the sun than '''Neptune''' on part of its orbit.\n\\end{definition}\n\n[Document 3]\n\\begin{definition}[Definition:New Moon]\nThe '''new moon''' is the astronomical phenomenon of the Moon in its orbit coming to its closest point to the Sun:\n:800px\nNote that the above diagram is not to scale.\nAt this point in its orbit, the Moon is between Earth and the Sun.\nThus the hemisphere of the Moon which is illuminated by the Sun is facing directly away from Earth.\nThus for an observer of the Moon from Earth, unless an actual solar eclipse is in progress, at this point it cannot be seen, because:\n:$(1): \\quad$ It is dark\n:$(2): \\quad$ The Sun is more or less behind it, outshining everything else in the sky.\nCategory:Definitions/Astronomy\n\\end{definition}\n\n[Document 4]\n\\begin{definition}[Definition:Phase of Moon]\nThe '''phase of the Moon''' is its apparent shape when viewed in the night sky of Earth.\nThis shape is dependent upon the position of the Moon with respect to the Sun and Earth.\n:800px\nWhen the Moon is between the Sun and Earth, the sunlit side faces more or less away from Earth, and so less than half of it can be seen lit up.\nWhen Earth is between the Sun and the Moon, the sunlit side faces more or less away towards Earth, and so more than half of it can be seen lit up.\nWhen the Moon is directly between the Sun and Earth, the sunlit side is facing completely away from Earth, and in normal conditions cannot be seen.\nThis is the '''phase''' known as '''new moon'''.\nWhen Earth is directly between the Sun and the Moon, the sunlit side is facing completely towards Earth, and in normal conditions appears as a brign disk.\nThis is the '''phase''' known as '''full moon'''.\nAt the point half way between new moon and full moon, the '''phase''' is known as '''first quarter'''.\nAt the point half way between full moon and new moon, the '''phase''' is known as '''last quarter'''.\nCategory:Definitions/Astronomy\n\\end{definition}\n\n[Document 5]\n\\section{Kepler's Laws of Planetary Motion/Third Law/Examples}\nTags: Kepler's Laws of Planetary Motion\n\n\\begin{theorem}\nLet $P$ be a planet orbiting the sun $S$\nLet $P$ be:\n:$\\text{(a)}: \\quad$ Twice as far away from $S$ as the Earth;\n:$\\text{(b)}: \\quad$ $3$ times as far away from $S$ as the Earth;\n:$\\text{(c)}: \\quad$ $25$ times as far away from $S$ as the Earth.\nThen the orbital period of $P$ is:\n:$\\text{(a)}: \\quad$ approximately $2.8$ years;\n:$\\text{(b)}: \\quad$ approximately $5.2$ years;\n:$\\text{(c)}: \\quad$ $125$ years.\n\\end{theorem}\n\n\\begin{proof}\nLet the orbital period of Earth be $T'$ years.\nLet the mean distance of Earth from $S$ be $A$.\nLet the orbital period of $P$ be $T$ years.\nLet the mean distance of $P$ from $S$ be $a$.\nBy Kepler's Third Law of Planetary Motion:\n{{begin-eqn}}\n{{eqn | l = \\dfrac {T'^2} {A^3}\n      | r = \\dfrac {T^2} {a^3}\n      | c = \n}}\n{{eqn | ll= \\leadsto\n      | l = T^2\n      | r = \\dfrac {a^3} {A^3}\n      | c = as $T'$ is $1$ year\n}}\n{{eqn | ll= \\leadsto\n      | l = T\n      | r = \\left({\\dfrac a A}\\right)^{3/2}\n      | c = \n}}\n{{end-eqn}}\nThus the required orbital periods are:\n:$\\text{(a)}: \\quad 2^{3/2} = 2 \\sqrt 2 \\approx 2.8$ years\n:$\\text{(b)}: \\quad 3^{3/2} = 3 \\sqrt 3 \\approx 5.2$ years\n:$\\text{(c)}: \\quad 25^{3/2} = 125$ years.\n{{qed}}\n\\end{proof}\n\n",
    "response": "<think>\nI need to calculate how long my spacecraft will take to orbit the Sun once, following Mercury's path. Mercury's average distance from the Sun is given as 58 million kilometers, and the mass of the Sun is 1.99 × 10^30 kg. I need the answer in Earth days.\n\nFirst, I recall that for planets orbiting the Sun, Kepler's third law applies. It states that the square of the orbital period is proportional to the cube of the semi-major axis. For the Sun, since it's much more massive, we can use:\n\n\\[ T^2 = \\frac{4\\pi^2}{GM} a^3 \\]\n\nwhere:\n- \\( T \\) is the orbital period,\n- \\( G \\) is the gravitational constant,\n- \\( M \\) is the mass of the Sun,\n- \\( a \\) is the semi-major axis, which for a circular orbit is just the radius.\n\nIn this case, the spacecraft is following Mercury's path, so it should have the same orbital period as Mercury, right? Because the period depends only on the semi-major axis for a given central mass.\n\nThe problem says \"closely following Mercury's path,\" and gives Mercury's average distance, which I assume is the semi-major axis. So yes, the orbital period should be the same as Mercury's.\n\nBut I need to calculate it using the given mass and distance.\n\nFrom Kepler's third law:\n\n\\[ T^2 = \\frac{4\\pi^2}{GM} a^3 \\]\n\nI have:\n- \\( M = 1.99 \\times 10^{30} \\) kg\n- \\( a = 58 \\times 10^6 \\) km\n\nBut units: I need to be consistent. Usually, we use meters and seconds.\n\nSo convert a to meters:\n58 million km = 58 × 10^6 km = 58 × 10^6 × 10^3 m = 58 × 10^9 m = 5.8 × 10^{10} m\n\n58 × 10^6 km is 58,000,000 km.\n1 km = 1000 m, so 58,000,000 km = 58,000,000,000 m = 5.8 × 10^{10} m. Yes.\n\nG, gravitational constant, I need that. It's not given in the problem, but I know it's approximately 6.674 × 10^{-11} N m² kg^{-2}, or in SI units, m³ kg^{-1} s^{-2}.\n\nI think I should use that.\n\nNow, plug into the formula.\n\nFirst, compute a^3.\n\na = 5.8 × 10^{10} m\n\na^3 = (5.8 × 10^{10})^3 = 5.8^3 × 10^{30}\n\n5.8^2 = 33.64\n\n33.64 × 5.8 = let's see, 30×5.8=174, 3.64×5.8≈3.64×6 - 3.64×0.2=21.84 - 0.728=21.112, better calculate properly.\n\n5.8 × 5.8 = (6-0.2)^2 = 36 - 2×6×0.2 + (0.2)^2 = 36 - 2.4 + 0.04 = 33.64, yes.\n\nNow 33.64 × 5.8:\n\n33.64 × 5 = 168.2\n\n33.64 × 0.8 = 26.912\n\nSo 168.2 + 26.912 = 195.112\n\nSo a^3 ≈ 195.112 × 10^{30} = 1.95112 × 10^{32} m³? No:\n\n(10^{10})^3 = 10^{30}, so 5.8^3 × 10^{30} = 195.112 × 10^{30} = 1.95112 × 10^{32} m³. Units are m³, yes.\n\nBut let's keep it as 1.951 × 10^{32} for now.\n\nNow, G = 6.674 × 10^{-11} m³ kg^{-1} s^{-2}\n\nM = 1.99 × 10^{30} kg\n\nSo GM = G × M = (6.674 × 10^{-11}) × (1.99 × 10^{30})\n\nFirst, 6.674 × 1.99\n\n6.674 × 2 = 13.348, minus 6.674 × 0.01 = 0.06674, so 13.348 - 0.06674? No, 1.99 = 2 - 0.01, but multiplication: better 6.674 × 1.99\n\n6.674 × 2 = 13.348\n\nBut since 1.99 is less, 6.674 × 1.99 = 6.674 × (2 - 0.01) = 13.348 - 0.06674 = 13.28126\n\nNow exponents: 10^{-11} × 10^{30} = 10^{19}\n\nSo GM ≈ 13.281 × 10^{19} = 1.3281 × 10^{20} m³ s^{-2}\n\nNow, 4π². π is approximately 3.1416, so π² ≈ 9.86902256, say 9.869\n\n4π² ≈ 4 × 9.869 = 39.476\n\nSo now, T² = [4π² / GM] × a³\n\nFirst, 4π² / GM = 39.476 / (1.3281 × 10^{20})\n\nCompute 39.476 / 1.3281 ≈ ?\n\nFirst, 1.3281 × 29 = 1.3281 × 30 - 1.3281 = 39.843 - 1.3281 = 38.5149\n\n39.476 - 38.5149 = 0.9611\n\nNow, 1.3281 × 0.723 ≈ ? Let's see, 1.3281 × 0.7 = 0.92967, 1.3281 × 0.023 = about 0.0305463, total 0.9602163, close to 0.9611.\n\nSo approximately 29.723\n\nBetter to divide directly.\n\n39.476 ÷ 1.3281\n\nCalculate: 1.3281 × 29.7 = 1.3281 × 30 - 1.3281 × 0.3 = 39.843 - 0.39843 = 39.44457\n\n39.476 - 39.44457 = 0.03143\n\nNow, 0.03143 / 1.3281 ≈ 0.02366, so total 29.72366\n\nSo about 29.724\n\nBut this is for 4π² / GM, and we have units: 39.476 / (1.3281 × 10^{20}) = (39.476 / 1.3281) × 10^{-20} ≈ 29.724 × 10^{-20} = 2.9724 × 10^{-19} s^{-2} m^{-3}? Let's see units.\n\nGM has units m³ s^{-2}, so 1/GM has units s² m^{-3}, so 4π² / GM has units s² m^{-3}.\n\nThen T² = [4π² / GM] × a³, which has (s² m^{-3}) × m³ = s², good.\n\nSo numerically, 4π² / GM ≈ 2.9724 × 10^{-19} s² m^{-3}? No:\n\n4π² / GM = 39.476 / (1.3281 × 10^{20}) = 2.9724 × 10^{-19} s² m^{-3}, yes.\n\nNow multiply by a³ = 1.95112 × 10^{32} m³\n\nSo T² = (2.9724 × 10^{-19}) × (1.95112 × 10^{32}) \n\nFirst, 2.9724 × 1.95112 ≈ ?\n\n2.9724 × 1.95 = 2.9724 × 2 - 2.9724 × 0.05 = 5.9448 - 0.14862 = 5.79618\n\nNow 2.9724 × 0.00112 = very small, about 0.003329, so total ≈ 5.799509\n\nBetter: 2.9724 × 1.95112\n\nCompute 29724 × 195112 / 10000 × 100000, messy.\n\n2.9724 × 1.95112 = 2.9724 × (1.95 + 0.00112) = 2.9724×1.95 + 2.9724×0.00112\n\n2.9724×1.95: 2.9724×2 = 5.9448, minus 2.9724×0.05 = 0.14862, so 5.9448 - 0.14862 = 5.79618? No, 1.95 = 2 - 0.05, so 5.9448 - 0.14862 = 5.79618, yes.\n\nThen 2.9724 × 0.00112 = 0.003329088\n\nSo total 5.79618 + 0.003329088 = 5.799509088\n\nNow exponents: 10^{-19} × 10^{32} = 10^{13}\n\nSo T² ≈ 5.7995 × 10^{13} s²\n\nThus T = sqrt(5.7995 × 10^{13}) seconds\n\nFirst, sqrt(5.7995 × 10^{13}) = sqrt(5.7995) × sqrt(10^{13}) = sqrt(5.7995) × 10^{6.5}\n\nsqrt(10^{13}) = 10^{13/2} = 10^{6.5} = 10^6 × 10^{0.5} = 1,000,000 × sqrt(10) ≈ 1,000,000 × 3.16227766 ≈ 3.16227766 × 10^6\n\nNow sqrt(5.7995) ≈ ? sqrt(4) = 2, sqrt(9) = 3, so between 2 and 3. sqrt(5.76) = 2.4, since 2.4^2=5.76, 5.7995 - 5.76 = 0.0395, derivative: increment ≈ 0.0395 / (2*2.4) = 0.0395/4.8 ≈ 0.008229, so sqrt(5.7995) ≈ 2.4 + 0.0082 = 2.4082\n\nMore accurately, 2.41^2 = 5.8081, which is higher than 5.7995, difference 0.0086, so adjust down: 0.0086 / (2*2.41) ≈ 0.0086/4.82 ≈ 0.001784, so sqrt(5.7995) ≈ 2.41 - 0.0018 = 2.4082, same as before.\n\nSo T ≈ 2.4082 × 3.16227766 × 10^6 s\n\nFirst, 2.4082 × 3.16227766\n\nCompute 2.4 × 3.16227766 = 7.589466384\n\n0.0082 × 3.16227766 ≈ 0.02593067692\n\nTotal ≈ 7.61539706092\n\nSo T ≈ 7.6154 × 10^6 seconds\n\nNow, convert to days. One Earth day is 24 hours × 60 minutes × 60 seconds = 86400 seconds.\n\nSo T in days = T_seconds / 86400\n\nT_seconds = 7.6154 × 10^6\n\n86400 = 8.64 × 10^4\n\nSo T_days = (7.6154 × 10^6) / (8.64 × 10^4) = (7.6154 / 8.64) × 10^{2}\n\n7.6154 / 8.64\n\nFirst, 8.64 × 0.8 = 6.912\n\n7.6154 - 6.912 = 0.7034\n\n8.64 × 0.0814 ≈ 8.64 × 0.08 = 0.6912, 8.64 × 0.0014 = 0.012096, total 0.703296\n\nClose to 0.7034, so approximately 0.8 + 0.0814 = 0.8814\n\nMore precisely, 0.7034 / 8.64 ≈ 0.0814, as above.\n\nSo 0.8814\n\nThen × 100 = 88.14 days? No:\n\n(7.6154 / 8.64) × 10^2 = 0.8814 × 100 = 88.14 days\n\nBut I think Mercury's orbital period is about 88 days, so that makes sense.\n\nBut let me check my calculations because it was messy.\n\nI recall that for Earth, a = 1 AU ≈ 1.496 × 10^{11} m, T = 1 year = 365.25 days ≈ 3.15576 × 10^7 seconds.\n\nIn the retrieved documents, Document 1 has a similar calculation, but for Earth.\n\nIn Document 5, there's an example using Kepler's third law with ratios.\n\nThat might be easier.\n\nFor Mercury, a_mercury = 58 million km.\n\nEarth's average distance is about 150 million km, I think.\n\n1 AU is defined as 149,597,870,700 meters, approximately 1.496 × 10^{11} m, or 149.6 million km.\n\nMercury is given as 58 million km.\n\nSo ratio a_mercury / a_earth = 58 / 149.6 ≈ ?\n\n58 ÷ 149.6\n\n149.6 ÷ 2 = 74.8, 58 / 74.8? No, a_merc / a_earth = 58e6 / 149.6e6 = 58 / 149.6\n\nSimplify: divide numerator and denominator by 2: 29 / 74.8\n\n74.8 ÷ 2 = 37.4, better decimal.\n\n58 ÷ 149.6 ≈ 0.3877\n\n149.6 × 0.3877 ≈ 149.6 × 0.3 = 44.88, 149.6 × 0.08 = 11.968, 149.6 × 0.007 = 1.0472, 149.6 × 0.0007 = 0.10472, total 44.88 + 11.968 = 56.848, +1.0472=57.8952, +0.10472=57.99992, close to 58.\n\nSo a_merc / a_earth ≈ 0.3877\n\nNow, from Kepler's third law, T^2 proportional to a^3, so T proportional to a^{3/2}\n\nSo T_merc / T_earth = (a_merc / a_earth)^{3/2} = (0.3877)^{1.5}\n\nFirst, (0.3877)^{1/2} = sqrt(0.3877)\n\nsqrt(0.36) = 0.6, sqrt(0.49) = 0.7, so around 0.6227? Calculate.\n\n0.62^2 = 0.3844, 0.3877 - 0.3844 = 0.0033, increment ≈ 0.0033 / (2*0.62) = 0.0033/1.24 ≈ 0.00266, so sqrt(0.3877) ≈ 0.62 + 0.00266 = 0.62266\n\nNow, (0.3877)^{3/2} = (0.3877) * sqrt(0.3877) ≈ 0.3877 * 0.62266\n\nCompute: 0.3877 * 0.6 = 0.23262\n\n0.3877 * 0.02266 ≈ 0.3877 * 0.02 = 0.007754, 0.3877 * 0.00266 ≈ 0.001031, total 0.008785\n\nSo total 0.23262 + 0.008785 = 0.241405\n\nSo T_merc / T_earth ≈ 0.2414\n\nT_earth = 365.25 days (tropical year, but for orbit, approximately)\n\nSo T_merc ≈ 0.2414 * 365.25\n\nFirst, 0.24 * 365.25 = 87.66\n\n0.0014 * 365.25 ≈ 0.51135\n\nTotal ≈ 88.17135 days\n\nAbout 88.17 days.\n\nSince a_merc = 58e6 km, a_earth = 149.6e6 km, so ratio r = 58/149.6 = 580/1496 = 145/374? Simplify.\n\nDivide numerator and denominator by 2: 29/74.8, but 74.8 is 748/10, better use fractions.\n\n58/149.6 = 580/1496 = 145/374\n\nSimplify by dividing by... 145 and 374, gcd? 145÷5=29, 374÷2=187, no common factors, so 29/74.8? 74.8 is 748/10, messy.\n\nUse decimal: 58 ÷ 149.6 = 580 ÷ 1496\n\n1496 ÷ 1496=1, 580/1496 ≈ 0.3877 as before.\n\nNow (0.3877)^{3/2} = (0.3877)^1.5\n\nSince T ∝ a^{3/2}, and a in AU.\n\na_merc in AU: 58e6 / 149.6e6 ≈ 0.3877 AU\n\nThen T in years = (a)^{3/2} = (0.3877)^{1.5}\n\nAs above, ≈ 0.2414 years\n\nThen in days: 0.2414 * 365.25 ≈ ?\n\n0.24 * 365.25 = 87.66\n\n0.0014 * 365.25 = 0.51135\n\nTotal 88.17135 days\n\nBut Mercury's actual orbital period is 87.97 days or something? I think it's about 88 days.\n\nIn the problem, it says \"average distance\", which for Mercury is semi-major axis, and orbital period is indeed approximately 88 Earth days.\n\nBut let me confirm with the given mass.\n\nIn Document 5, it has examples, like for twice the distance, T=2^{3/2}=2√2≈2.828 years, etc.\n\nBut here, a_merc = 0.3877 AU, so T = (0.3877)^{3/2} years.\n\nBut since I have the mass, I should use the formula to be precise.\n\nEarlier I got T ≈ 7.6154 × 10^6 seconds, divided by 86400.\n\n86400 seconds/day.\n\nT_seconds = 7.6154e6\n\n86400 = 8.64e4\n\nT_days = 7.6154e6 / 8.64e4 = 7.6154e6 / 86400\n\nCompute numerically: 7615400 / 86400\n\nFirst, divide by 100: 76154 / 864\n\nNow, 864 × 88 = 864 × 100 - 864 × 12 = 86400 - 10368 = 76032? Better:\n\n864 × 80 = 69120\n\n864 × 8 = 6912\n\nTotal 69120 + 6912 = 76032\n\n76154 - 76032 = 122\n\nSo 88 + 122/864\n\nSimplify 122/864, divide by 2: 61/432 ≈ 0.1412\n\nSo 88.1412 days\n\nEarlier with ratio I got 88.17, slight difference due to approximation.\n\nBut in my first calculation, I used a=5.8e10 m, but Earth's a is 1.496e11 m, ratio 5.8e10 / 1.496e11 = 0.3877, same.\n\nIn first method, I had T^2 = 5.7995e13 s^2\n\nT = sqrt(5.7995e13) = sqrt(5.7995)*10^{6.5}\n\nsqrt(5.7995)≈2.4085? Earlier I had 2.4082\n\n2.4085^2 = ? 2.4^2=5.76, 0.0085*2*2.4=0.0408, better (2.4 + 0.0085)^2=2.4^2 + 2*2.4*0.0085 + (0.0085)^2=5.76 + 0.0408 + 0.00007225≈5.80087225, close to 5.7995, slightly high.\n\nSo adjust: difference -0.00137225, derivative 2*2.4085≈4.817, decrement -0.00137225 / 4.817 ≈ -0.000285, so sqrt≈2.4085 - 0.000285≈2.408215\n\nSame as before.\n\nThen sqrt(10^{13})=10^{6.5}=3162277.66\n\n2.408215 * 3162277.66 ≈ ?\n\nFirst, 2.4 * 3162277.66 = 7589466.384\n\n0.008215 * 3162277.66 ≈ 0.008 * 3162277.66 = 25298.22128, 0.000215*3162277.66≈679.889, total ≈25298.221 + 679.889=25978.11\n\nSo total T≈7589466.384 + 25978.11 = 7615444.494 s\n\nNow /86400 = 7615444.494 / 86400\n\n86400 * 88 = 86400*100 - 86400*12 = 8640000 - 1036800 = 7603200? Earlier 864*88=76032, but that's for thousands.\n\n86400 * 88 = 86400 * 100 - 86400 * 12 = 8,640,000 - 1,036,800 = 7,603,200\n\nT=7,615,444.494\n\nDifference: 7,615,444.494 - 7,603,200 = 12,244.494\n\nNow 86400 * 0.1417 ≈ ? First, 86400 * 0.1 = 8640\n\n86400 * 0.04 = 3456\n\n86400 * 0.0017 = 146.88\n\nTotal 8640 + 3456 = 12096, +146.88=12242.88\n\nClose to 12244.494, difference 1.614, so add 1.614/86400≈0.0000187, negligible.\n\nSo T≈88 + 0.1417 = 88.1417 days\n\nBut this is for the spacecraft, same as Mercury.\n\nIn the problem, I have the mass given, but in this calculation, I used G, which is standard.\n\nIn Document 1, it has G=6.674e-11, same as I used.\n\nAnd mass of Sun is given as 1.99e30 kg, which matches.\n\nBut in my calculation, I got about 88.14 days.\n\nI know that Mercury's actual sidereal orbital period is 87.969 days, but here we're using average distance, so it should be fine.\n\nPerhaps I can use the formula directly with the given values.\n\nSet up the equation.\n\nT^2 = (4 * pi^2 * a^3) / (G * M)\n\na = 58e6 km = 5.8e10 m\n\nBut let's keep in km, but G is in m^3, so need consistent units.\n\nG = 6.67430e-11 m^3 kg^{-1} s^{-2} (I'll use 6.674e-11)\n\nM = 1.99e30 kg\n\na = 58e9 m? 58 million km = 58e6 km = 58e6 * 1000 m = 58e9 m = 5.8e10 m, yes.\n\n58e9 is 5.8e10, same.\n\npi = 3.1415926535\n\npi^2 ≈ 9.869604401\n\n4pi^2 ≈ 39.478417604\n\na^3 = (5.8e10)^3 = 5.8^3 * 10^{30} = 195.112 * 10^{30} = 1.95112e32 m^3\n\nGM = 6.674e-11 * 1.99e30 = let's compute:\n\n6.674e-11 * 1.99e30 = 6.674 * 1.99 * 10^{19}\n\n6.674 * 2 = 13.348\n\n6.674 * 0.01 = 0.06674, so 13.348 - 0.06674? No, 1.99 = 2 - 0.01, but multiplication: 6.674 * 1.99 = 6.674*(2 - 0.01) = 13.348 - 0.06674 = 13.28126\n\nSo 1.328126e1 * 10^{19} = 1.328126e20\n\nNow, 4pi^2 a^3 = 39.478417604 * 1.95112e32 ≈ ?\n\nFirst, 39.478417604 * 1.95112e32\n\nCompute 39.478417604 * 1.95112\n\nFirst, 40 * 1.95112 = 78.0448, but better:\n\n39.478417604 * 1.95112 ≈ 39.478417604 * (2 - 0.04888) = 78.956835208 - ? Messy.\n\n39.478417604 * 1.95 = 39.478417604 * 2 - 39.478417604 * 0.05 = 78.956835208 - 1.9739208802 = 76.9829143278\n\nThen 39.478417604 * 0.00112 = 0.0442118274768\n\nTotal ≈ 76.9829143278 + 0.0442118274768 = 77.0271261552768\n\nSo approximately 7.7027e1 * 10^{32} = 7.7027e33? No:\n\n39.478 * 1.95112e32 ≈ but 39.478 * 1.95112 ≈ 77.027, as above, and since a^3 is e32, so 7.7027e33? Let's see:\n\n39.478e0 * 1.95112e32 = 7.7027e33, yes.\n\nBut I have more digits, but approximately.\n\nNow divide by GM: 7.7027e33 / 1.328126e20 = ?\n\n7.7027e33 / 1.328126e20 = 7.7027 / 1.328126 * 10^{13}\n\nCompute 7.7027 / 1.328126 